Specialty Coffee Analysis

Speciality Coffee Predictors Analysis

Eduardo Pacheco & Abert Figueras

23/02/2022

1 1. Overview

1.1 What is Specialty Coffee?

The term ‘Speciality coffee’ or ‘Specialty coffee’ is used to refer to coffee that is graded 80 points or above on a 100 point scale by a certified coffee taster from the Specialty Coffee Association of Europe (SCAE) or by a licensed Q Grader from the Quality Coffee Institute (CQI).

Specialty coffees are coffees at their peak and are different to other coffee because specialty coffee has been grown at the perfect altitude, at the correct time of year, in the best soil, and then picked at just the right time. All this translates into some of the most exciting and tasty coffee in the world.

1.2 Specialty Coffee - Q Grade Score Sheet

SCORE GRADE SPECIALITY YES/NO
90 - 100 Outstanding Specialty Coffee
85 - 89.99 Excellent Specialty Coffee
80 - 84.99 Very Good Specialty Coffee
Less than 80 Below Specialty Coffee Not Specialty Coffee

1.3 Coffee Grading

Green coffee is graded via visual inspection and cupping. Visual inspection involves taking a 350g sample of green coffee beans and counting defective beans. Defects can be Primary (e.g. black beans, sour beans) or Secondary (e.g. broken beans). For a coffee to qualify as “specialty”, it must have zero Primary defects and less than five Secondary defects.

Cupping involves roasting the coffee and brewing simply with hot water, and relies on the skill of the taster to assign scores to each of the coffee’s attributes, such the acidity, body, flavor and aroma.

1.4 Growth of Specialty Coffee

In the USA, specialty coffee is spreading nationwide, daily consumption of specialty coffee in America has risen from 9% in 1999 to 34% in 2014.

Meanwhile, in the UK, a recent report by Allegra predicts that the specialty coffee market is set for a 13% year on year growth, higher than the 10% predicted for the coffee market as a whole. The result of speciality coffees increasing popularity is mirrored in high street chains, as Starbucks and Costa continue to introduce limited edition single origin coffees in stark contrast to their super-dark roasts or high robusta-content blends. Allegra’s report also predicted a doubling of the current 1,400 specialty coffee shops by 2020, and a year on year growth rate of 17% for the UK roasted specialty coffee market.

In this context, we have decided to analyse a sample of 1339 specialty coffees from all over the world, with the purpose of identify which are the main factor that influence the coffee grading total score.

2 2. Introduction

2.1 2.1. Where the data comes from

We have extracted the data from a coffee trader here in Switzerland, it is a small sample from their data bank of coffees. We had tried to randomly select a representative sample from the large coffee portfolio of this company.

2.2 2.2. What the aims of the analysis are

We have decided to take the role of a coffee broker. In other words, a coffee broker is a coffee specialist whose mission is to search and discover new farms and suppliers. To have some guidelines and criteria to select the best candidates and collect samples, we are approaching this analysis under the following research question:

“Which coffee characteristics (predictor variables) have the most significant influence in the cupper score (response variable) for Specialty Coffees, in the function of the criteria established by the European Coffee Association.”

In the upper-right graph, we observe that most of the entries correspond to the coffee specie Arabica. This is because Robusta is mainly used to add body and texture to coffee blends. For this reason, we will give special attention to the results from the Arabica coffees.

In the upper right, the most common processing method in the Washed/Wet, about 40% of the samples has been produced in this way in this sample. In the lower right the moisture. Not all coffee producers have the resources to measure the moisture of the coffee beans. Because of this, we observe that a large proportion of the measurements fall in the cero value, which makes no sense. All organic matter has some level of moisture.

In the lower right, we have the altitude. We can notice how rare it is for farmers to have coffee plantations over two thousand meters above sea level (ASL). It is also rare to see coffee plantations under 500 meter ASL.

lowerFn <- function(data, mapping, method = "lm", ...) {
  p <- ggplot(data = data, mapping = mapping) +
    geom_point(colour = "steelblue1") +
    geom_smooth(method = method, color = "firebrick1", ...)
  p
}

pairs.correlation <- ggpairs(
  coffee[, 10:19], lower = list(continuous = wrap(lowerFn, method = "lm", size = 0.3)),
  diag = list(continuous = wrap("barDiag", colour = "steelblue1")),
  upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 2)),
  title = "Correlation Matrix of Coffee Characteristics") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size=6),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 6))

pairs.correlation

5 5. Chapter of Choice

R package corrplot provides a visual exploratory tool on correlation matrix that supports automatic variable reordering to help detect hidden patterns among variables.

Corrplot is very easy to use and provides a rich array of plotting options in visualization method, graphic layout, color, legend, text labels, etc. It also provides p-values and confidence intervals to help users determine the statistical significance of the correlations.

corrplot() has about 50 parameters, however the mostly common ones are only a few. We can get a correlation matrix plot with only one line of code in most scenes. The mostly using parameters include method, type, order, diag, and etc.

There are seven visualization methods (parameter method) in corrplot package, named ‘circle’, ‘square’, ‘ellipse’, ‘number’, ‘shade’, ‘color’, ‘pie’. Color intensity of the glyph is proportional to the correlation coefficients by default color setting.

library(corrplot)
corrplot(correlation, method="color", tl.cex = 0.9, tl.col = "black")

library(corrplot)
corrplot(correlation, method="number", number.cex = 0.8, tl.cex = 0.9, tl.col = "black")

A nice combination of two different methods:

corrplot(correlation, method = 'color', order = 'original', addCoef.col = 'black',
         number.cex = 0.8, tl.cex = 0.9, tl.col = "black")

6 6. Fitting Statistical Models

6.1 6.1. Categorical Variables

Categorical variables cannot be analysed the same way as continuous variables. For this reason, we will not try to fit linear models to find insights, except for Species. Instead we will be doing Box plots.

6.1.1. Total cup score by Specie:

Formulate null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis

Null hypothesis: Arabica and Robusta have the same mean.
\(Ho : \mu Ar = \mu Ro\)

Alternative Hypothesis: Arabica and Robusta means are NOT equal.
\(Ha : \mu Ar \ne \mu B\)

t.test(Total.Cup.Score ~ Species, data = coffee, altervative = "two.sided", )

ggplot(data = coffee,
       mapping = aes(y = Total.Cup.Score,
                     x = factor(Species))) +
  ggtitle("Total Cup Score by Specie") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,
                                  size = 9,
                                  face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 7),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 9)) +
  stat_boxplot(geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "steelblue1",
               outlier.colour = "indianred1",
               outlier.alpha = 0.5,
               outlier.size = 1)

## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Total.Cup.Score by Species
## t = 2.8028, df = 28.415, p-value = 0.009028
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Arabica and group Robusta is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.353131 2.266233
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Arabica mean in group Robusta 
##              82.17861              80.86893

The p-value = 0.009028 makes us reject the Null Hypothesis.

We can obtain several insights, just to mention some:

Both species, Arabica and Robusta, have similar smallest “normal observation. Both interquartile ranges have approximately the same size, but Arabicas start one point higher.

There is none robiusta coffee to be found over 84 points. On the other hand,
about 25% of arabica coffees score 84 points of higher

6.2 6.2. Fitting Models in Continuous Variables

Here again, we will not be using the variable “Total.Cup.Points” as the response variable since it is the result of adding all measured values. Instead, we will use “Cupper.Score” to run linear models in function of the coffee characteristics.

6.2.1. Cupper Score in function of the Moisture

fit.cupperscore.moisture <- lm(Cupper.Score  ~ Moisture, data = coffee)
summary(fit.cupperscore.moisture)

ggplot(data = coffee,
       mapping = aes(y = Cupper.Score,
                     x = Moisture)) +
  ggtitle("Cupper Score vs Moisture") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,
                                  size = 17,
                                  face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 15),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 16)) +
  xlab("Moisture") +
  ylab("Cupper Score") +
  geom_point(col="steelblue1", cex = 1.5, pch = 1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(coffee$Cupper.Score), colour = "blue", size = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', col="firebrick1", se=FALSE, size = 0.6)

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Cupper.Score ~ Moisture, data = coffee)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.30198 -0.22198  0.01092  0.21511  2.52802 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  7.66002    0.02389 320.703  < 2e-16 ***
## Moisture    -1.70946    0.23722  -7.206 9.59e-13 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.4189 on 1336 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.03741,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.03669 
## F-statistic: 51.93 on 1 and 1336 DF,  p-value: 9.595e-13

We can describe our linear regression model with the following equation: \[f(Cupper.Score) = {7.66} - {1.71} Moisture\]

We obtain the following conclusions:

For an extra 0.01 of moisture, the cupper score decreases by 1.71. Which denotes a negative relation, the higher the moisture, the lower the score.

The p-values = 9.595e-13 confirms the high signicancy in therelation between the moisture and the cupper score.

The aglomeration of dots in the plot between 0.9 and 0.14, confirms what the International Coffee Organization (ICO) states, that the ideal moisture content of green beans ready for roasting should be between 8% and 12.5%. This range is generally considered the optimum for factors such as cup quality.

6.2.2. Cupper Score in function of the One-defect Category

fit.cupperscore.onedefect <- lm(Cupper.Score  ~ Category.One.Defects, data = coffee)

ggplot(data = coffee,
       mapping = aes(y = Cupper.Score,

                                  face = "bold"),

  xlab("One-Defects Category") +

We can describe our linear regression model with the following equation: \[f(Cupper.Score) = {7.51} - {0.006} Category.One.Defects\]

We obtain the following conclusions:

For one extra value in one-defect category, the cupper score decreases by 0.006. Which denotes a negative relation, the more defects, the lower the score.

The p-values = 0.19 shows low signicancy in the relation between the cupper score and the one-defect category.

6.3.9. Cupper Score in function of the Sweetness

We can describe our linear regression model with the following equation: \[f(Cupper.Score) = {7.26} + {0.0253} Sweetness\]

We obtain the following conclusions:

For one extra value in sweetness, the cupper score increase by 0.0253. Which denotes a positive relation, the more sweetness, the higher the score.

The p-values = 2.30e-1 shows low signicancy in the relation between the cupper score and the sweetness.

7 7. General conclusions

  • It would be recommended to provide support and training to the producer which does not measure values like moisture, altitude, or processing method. As well as to identify to which species and variety do belong the coffee beans they are producing. All these are in order to complete the data set and set a proper documentation process for future analysis.

  • It would be highly recommended to try to identify which type of variety are the unknown coffees, classified as “Other”, as they represent approximately 25% of the whole sample. This group has many similar scores and dispersion behaviour as Typica and Bourbon, it could be possible to find important insight inside this group.

  • About 60% of the coffee from Haiti is below the 80-points cupper score, which means most of it does not fall in the speciality coffee category. It would be recommended to evaluate how profitable is to buy this coffee. But as we do not have financial data, it would depend on the business strategy of the trading company.

  • On average the Processing Method does not affect the scores of the coffees inside this sample. Each group has more than 50 % of the coffees in between the 80 to 85 points range. We can observe that honey washed coffees had become a high-quality product, with 100% of these coffees are above the 80 points score. It might be worth it to buy more Honey coffee beans.

  • Best coffees are to be found in between the 1000 to 2000-meter altitude. Excepting a large group which falls in the 500 to 600 meters range. In order to increase the quality of the coffees on sale, it would be recommended to consider buying just coffees harvested above the 1000 meters.

  • We have discovered that many of the coffee characteristics have extreme high significance concerning the cupper score as a response variable. To visually observe these p-values, we have ordered the coffee characteristics decreasingly in the function of the significance as follows:

ORDER CHARACTERISTIC P-VALUE SIGNIFICANCE
1 Flavor 2.73e-230 Very High
2 Aftertaste 1.57e-221 Very High
3 Balance 7.11e-159 Very High
4 Acidity 4.33e-138 Very High
5 Aroma 8.03e-130 Very High
6 Body 4.17e-95 Very High
7 Clean Cup 2.48e- 19 High
8 Sweetness 0.230 None

The last table could be of great use for both, supplier and buyers. As it shows which coffees characteristics are more considered when a coffee taster assesses a coffee sample.

  • We consider that more important than the coffee characteristics are the following variables, also sorted decreasingly in the function of the significance:
ORDER CHARACTERISTIC P-VALUE SIGNIFICANCE
1 Two Defects Category 1.13e-15 High
2 Moisture 9.595e-13 High
3 Altitude 9.5e-7 High
4 One Defects Category 1.9e-1 None

We would recommend focusing on these variables, as it is possible to change them. In other words, we can try to implement changes on them, so we can improve the individual scores. Therefore, to improve the Cupper Score and the Total Cupping Score.
